Seminar Held in Mongolia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- A seminar on the theme of "The Juche Idea and Korea Today" was held by the Centre for the Study of the Juche Idea of Chinggis Khan University of Mongolia on Oct. 26.
 On display in the venue of the seminar were photos showing the revolutionary activities of President Kim Il Sung and leader Kim Jong Il and photos dealing with the advantages of the socialist system in the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The vice-president of the University said that the Korean people are waging a dynamic struggle to build a great prosperous powerful socialist nation under the banner of the Juche idea and achieve the independent and peaceful reunification of Korea. He went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Il Sung fathered the Juche idea and built a unique socialist country centered on the popular masses. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK is successfully protecting the sovereignty and dignity of the country with the Songun politics of Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We are highly proud of having awarded our university's honorable doctorate to him in 2001 in high recognition of his ideological and theoretical exploits.
 Head of a chair of the university N. Bold noted that the imperialists are increasing pressure upon the DPRK such as economic sanctions and blockade in an attempt to deter it from advancing along the road of independence. But the Korean people are firmly defending the sovereignty of their country, meeting all challenges of the imperialists, under the banner of the Songun politics of Kim Jong Il, he added: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK is the most developed socialist country centered on the popular masses quite different from what the Western countries say about it. 
 He said he would conduct positive activities for the study of the Juche idea including the holding of seminars and briefings so as to help more many teachers and students grasp the advantages of Korean-style socialism and expand the ranks of the centre.

Japanese Government Urged to Compensate Former "Comfort Women" 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- Amnesty International released a report on the issue of the "comfort women" for the imperial Japanese army on Oct. 28 against the backdrop of the growing world public voices demanding Japan apologize and compensate for its past crimes.
 Amnesty International asserted in its report that the "above-mentioned issue is a violation of international law and the Japanese government is, therefore, obliged to make a legal compensation to the former 'comfort women'". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The report continued: The above-mentioned crimes are war crimes and quite contrary to humanism as they are evidence proving the most heartbreaking sexual slavery. It is not a simple moral duty for the Japanese government to compensate for those crimes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It urged the Japanese government to take an effective measure for making an urgent adequate compensation to the former "comfort women" and advised it to work out a report on their status. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It also demanded the Diet admit its responsibility and apologize to them.

U.S. Forces in S. Korea Stage Evacuation Drill of Noncombatants 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- The U.S. forces in south Korea staged an exercise of evacuating noncombatants to Japan allegedly to cope with a contingency, according to the south Korean KBS.
 They evacuated noncombatants including GI families to the U.S. air base in Iwakuni of Japan by clippers and by air on Oct. 28 and brought them back to south Korea two days later. This was disclosed by "The Stars and Stripes" published by the U.S. Department of Defense. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The recent drill was staged at a time when the U.S. is holding a war confab with the south Korean trigger-happy elements after working out "OPLAN 5027-04", a new war scenario to mount a preemptive nuclear attack on the north. This clearly indicates that the U.S. preparations for a war of aggression have already reached a final phase. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. should stop at once such reckless war moves designed to chill the atmosphere of the forthcoming 5th six-party talks.

Indian Diplomats Visit Wasan Middle School 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- N.T. Khankhup, Indian ambassador to the DPRK, and embassy officials visited Korea-India Friendship Pyongyang Wasan Middle School on Nov. 3.
 Being briefed on the educational work and management of the school, the guests looked round educational facilities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They enjoyed an art performance given by students and talked to each other about the need to further develop cultural exchange between the two countries, deepening the friendship feelings. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ambassador wished the school contributing to the activities for friendship between the two countries greater success in its work.

Cadres Visit Pyongyang 326 Electric Wire Factory 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- Some days ago leader  Kim Jong Il gave field guidance to the Pyongyang 326 Electric Wire Factory and expressed great satisfaction over the fact that the officials and workers of the factory have put all production processes on a modern and scientific basis, upholding the Workers' Party of Korea's line of attaching importance to science and built the compound of the factory as required by the new century.
 Kim Yong Nam, Pak Pong Ju and other cadres, leading officials, commissions and ministries of the Cabinet and national institutions and chief secretaries of provincial committees of the WPK and leading officials of factories and enterprises visited the factory on Nov. 3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The visitors were deeply moved to see a variety of electric wire and products pouring out at the factory furnished with up-to-date equipment and production processes modernized and scientized by officials and workers of the factory. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They saw an art performance given by the art squad of the factory. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Sung Hyon, minister of Metal Industry, said that visiting the factory, he keenly felt the validity and vitality of the line of attaching importance to science and technology set forth by Kim Jong Il.

U.S. Occupation Forces' Arbitrary Practices in S. Korea Assailed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- The U.S. forces side in south Korea whisked away their soldier, who ruthlessly drove a truck over a south Korean woman to death in Tongduchon, Kyonggi Province in June last, without any trial or punishment, claiming that he did not do anything wrong. This fact was disclosed by south Korean media recently.
 Commenting on this, Rodong Sinmun Friday observes that this arbitrary practice of the U.S. forces is nothing but a repetition of their killing of Sin Hyo Sun and Sim Mi Son. It denounces the case as a crime against the Korean nation, a clear indication of the U.S. imperialist aggression troops' arrogant behavior of damaging its dignity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The commentary goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialist aggression troops do not consider the killing of civilians as a crime and take their man-killing no more serious than pilfering.
 The U.S. is not in a position to talk about someone's "human rights performance" and it is, indeed, a human rights abuser that should face an international human rights trial. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 There are ample facts to prove this. The recent murder of a south Korean woman by the U.S. aggression troop there and their manner whereby they handled the case heighten the south Korean's vigilance against the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The recent murder case as horrendous as the killing of Sin Hyo Sun and Sim Mi Son will continue to occur and put the south Koreans in a nightmare of horror and disgrace as long as the U.S. imperialist aggression troops, a huge group of human ogres defying law and reason, remain in south Korea.
 The reality requires the south Korean people to stage the same anti-U.S. candlelight demonstrations as what raged in south Korea three years ago, making the U.S. shudder in order not to suffer bigger national misfortune and disgrace due to the occupation forces.

Exhibition and Art Competition among Schoolchildren's Palaces and Halls across Country Held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- An exhibition of inventions and teaching aids and an art competition among the schoolchildren's palaces and halls across the country took place here.
 On display in the venue were more than 500 inventions and teaching aids presented by teachers and schoolchildren from different schoolchildren's palaces and halls across the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Highly appreciated at the exhibition were "Revolving visual aids showing the eight sceneries in the era of Songun", "Visual aids for educating children in the history of Songun leadership," "A robot for education" and "A device comprehensively teaching guitar chords" presented by the Mangyongdae Schoolchildren's Palace and "A remote controlled-rocket launcher" and "A computer program for learning calligraphy" by the Pyongyang Schoolchildren's Palace,  "A computer program for three phase alternating current circuit (light)" by the Schoolchildren's Hall in Huichon, "Folding visual aids for industrial art" by the Schoolchildren's Hall in Hyongjesan District, Pyongyang,  and  "A self-study book for accordion" by the Schoolchildren's Hall in Sunchon and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, members of hobby groups of different schoolchildren's palaces and halls across the country contributed at least 250 paintings of diverse kinds including Korean paintings, oil paintings and watercolors with main emphasis on rough sketches. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Those art works well showcased the skills of the schoolchildren growing up to be Juche-oriented painters.

Nepalese Public Figure's Impressions of Korea
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- Kamal Prasad Chaulagain who is heading a delegation of the National Integrated Study and Research Centre of Nepal had an interview with the KCNA before his return home.
 He said that he was deeply moved to see proud successes achieved by the Korean people in building a great prosperous powerful socialist nation under the Songun leadership of Kim Jong Il. He went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Leader Kim Jong Il made the revolutionary history of President Kim Il Sung continue in this land by his ever-victorious Songun politics.
 He developed in depth the Songun idea and line of President Kim Il Sung and put forward the invincible Songun political mode, which is one of his brilliant exploits performed in the work for development and prosperity of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The single-minded unity of the whole army and the people around the headquarters of the revolution with Kim Jong Il as its head is a decisive guarantee for the victory of the Korean revolution. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The feature of Korea forming a harmonious whole is miraculous one unprecedented in the history of the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The unbreakable, single-minded unity of the leader, the Party and masses in Korea, this is the invincible unity consistent with the absolute respect and trust of the Korean people in their leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 I am convinced that Korea led by Kim Jong Il, great brilliant commander of Songun absolutely revered and respected by the Korean people and the world progressive people, will be ever powerful and prosperous.

Kim Jong Il Sends Gifts to Arirang Creators and Performers
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 4 (KCNA) -- Leader Kim Jong Il sent gifts to the creators and performers of the grand gymnastic and artistic performance "Arirang."
 The Kim Il Sung Prize Winner Arirang was reproduced on the occasions of the 60th anniversaries of the Workers' Party of Korea and the liberation of Korea and was performed before audiences on 62 occasions, evoking lively repercussions among south Koreans, overseas compatriots and foreigners, to say nothing of those in the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jong Il spared time to watch the performance three times, highly estimated it and extended thanks to its participants and sent to all of them gifts to be handed down through generations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the creators and performers were immensely pleased and excited to receive the gifts on Nov. 3.
